00:03:57.265 --> 00:03:58.640
If you remember
now, we're trying

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:03.500
to track the number of neutrons
in some small energy group, e,

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:06.940
traveling in some
small direction, omega.

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:09.110
And those have little
vector things on it

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:12.417
at some specific position
as a function of time.

00:04:12.417 --> 00:04:14.750
So in order to figure out how
many neutrons are entering

00:04:14.750 --> 00:04:16.820
our group from fission,
we need to know,

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:18.589
what are all the
fissions happening

00:04:18.589 --> 00:04:20.310
in all the other groups?

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:22.730
I've also escalated this
problem a little bit

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:26.060
to not assume that the
reactor's homogeneous.

00:04:26.060 --> 00:04:29.330
So I've added an r, or
a spatial dependence

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:31.528
for every cross-section
here, which

00:04:31.528 --> 00:04:33.320
