different materials.

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:37.250
You almost certainly
will, unless your reactor

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:38.470
has been in a blender.

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:40.790
So except for that
case, you would actually

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:44.390
have different cross sections in
different parts of the reactor.

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:45.890
So all of a sudden,
this is starting

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:48.830
to get awfully interesting,
or messy depending on what

00:04:48.830 --> 00:04:50.150
you want to think about it.

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:52.760
There is the external
source, which is actually

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:55.910
a real phenomenon,
because reactors

00:04:55.910 --> 00:04:59.430
do stick in those californium
kickstarter sources.

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:01.040
So for some amount
of time, there

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:03.140
is an external
source of neutrons,

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:06.050
giving them out with some
positional energy angle

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:08.260
and time dependence.

00:05:08.260 --> 00:05:10.270
So let's call this the
kickstarter source.

00:05:14.650 --> 00:05:19.720
There's this term right
here, the nin reactions.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:25.550
So these are other reactions
where it's absorb a neutron,

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:29.420
and give off anywhere
between 2 and 4 neutrons.

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:31.460
Beyond that, it's
just not energetically

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:33.230
possible in a fission reactor.

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:34.880
But don't undergo fission.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:37.730
They have their own cross
sections, their own birth

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:38.720
spectrum.

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:40.610
And I've stuck in
something right here,

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:43.460
if we have summing over all
possible i, where you have

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:48.920
this reaction be n in reaction,
where 1 neutron goes in,

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:50.790
and i neutrons come out.

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:53.450
You've got to multiply
by the number of neutrons

00:05:53.450 --> 00:05:54.840
per reaction.

00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:57.060
For fission, that was new.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.875
For an nin reaction,
that's just i.

00:05:59.875 --> 00:06:01.500
But otherwise, the
term looks the same.

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:05.490
You have your multiplier,
your birth spectrum, your 4pi,

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.730
your integral over stuff,
your unique cross-section,

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:10.530
and the flux.

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:12.920
And these two together
give you a reaction rate.

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:15.740
I've just written all of the
differentials as d stuff,

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:17.840
because it takes a lot
of time to write those

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:19.450
over and over again.

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:26.050
And then we have our
photo fission term,

00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:28.520
where gamma rays of
sufficiently high energy

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:32.000
can also induce fission
external to the neutrons.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.140
The term looks exactly the same.

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:36.350
There's going to be some
new for photofission,

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:38.510
some birth spectrum
for photofission,

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:41.090
some cross section for
photofission, and the same flux

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:43.430
that we're using
everywhere else.

00:06:43.430 --> 00:06:53.120
Then we had what's called the in
scattering term, where neutrons

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:55.760
can undergo scattering,
lose some energy,

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:58.880
and enter our group
from somewhere else.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:01.400
That's why we have
those en omega primes,

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:03.110
because it's some
other energy group.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.320
And we have to account for
all of those energy groups.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:08.570
That's why we have
this integral there.

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:10.470
And it looks very much the same.

00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:12.530
There's a scattering
cross-section.

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:16.080
And that should actually
be an e prime right there.

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:17.570
Make sure I'm not
missing any more

00:07:17.570 --> 00:07:21.110
of those inside the integral.

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:26.480
That's all good.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.000
That's a prime, good.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:30.020
There's also a flux.

00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:32.180
And then there was this
probability function

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:35.780
that a given neutron
starting off an energy

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:38.926
e prime omega prime,
ends up scattering into r

00:07:38.926 --> 00:07:40.460
energy, e and omega.

00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:44.130
So this would be the other one.

00:07:44.130 --> 00:07:47.100
And this would be r group.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:50.530
But otherwise, the term
looks very much the same.

00:07:50.530 --> 00:07:53.310
And that takes care of all
the possible gains of neutrons

00:07:53.310 --> 00:07:54.630
into r group.

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:56.680
The losses are a
fair bit simpler.

00:07:56.680 --> 00:08:00.490
There is reaction of
absolutely any kind.

00:08:00.490 --> 00:08:08.770
Let's say this would be the
total cross-section, which

00:08:08.770 --> 00:08:11.380
says that if a neutron
undergoes any reaction at all,

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:16.120
it's going to lose energy and
go out of our energy group d, e.

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:17.770
Notice here that these are all--

00:08:17.770 --> 00:08:20.320
these energies and omega
is our all r group,

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:22.750
because we only care about
how many neutrons in r group

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:24.940
undergo a reaction and leave.

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:26.710
And the form is very simple--

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:31.130
integrate over volume,
energy, and direction,

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:33.700
times a cross-section,
times a flux,

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:35.559
just like all the other ones.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:37.420
Then the only difference
in one right here

00:08:37.420 --> 00:08:38.545
is what we'll call leakage.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:46.120
These are neutrons moving
out of whatever control

00:08:46.120 --> 00:08:47.370
surface that we're looking at.

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:53.790
And this can be some arbitrarily
complex control surface in 3D.

00:08:53.790 --> 00:08:55.770
I don't really know how
to draw a blob in 3D.

00:08:55.770 --> 00:08:58.380
But at every point
on that blob, there's

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:00.510
going to be a normal vector.

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:05.340
And you can then take the
current of neutrons traveling

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:08.280
out that normal vector, and
figure out how much of that

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:11.340
is actually leaving
our surface ds.

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:13.620
The one problem we had
is that everything here

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:18.000
is in terms of volume,
volume, volume, surface.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:19.770
So we don't have
all the same terms,

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:22.410
because once we have everything
in the same variables

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:26.190
we can start to make some
pretty crazy simplifications.

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:33.830
The last thing we did is we
invoked the divergence theorem,

00:09:33.830 --> 00:09:39.100
that says that the surface
integral of some variable FdS

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:43.750
is the same as the volume
integral of the divergence

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:47.167
of that variable dV.

00:09:47.167 --> 00:09:49.250
So I remember there was
some snickering last time,

00:09:49.250 --> 00:09:51.125
because you probably
haven't seen this since,

00:09:51.125 --> 00:09:53.140
was it 1801 or 1802?

00:09:53.140 --> 00:09:56.480
1802, OK, that makes sense,
because divergence usually

00:09:56.480 --> 00:09:59.060
has more than one variable
associated with it.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:00.560
I'll include the
dot, because that's

00:10:00.560 --> 00:10:02.450
what makes that divergence.

00:10:02.450 --> 00:10:05.790
So we can then
rewrite this term.

00:10:05.790 --> 00:10:08.120
Let's start our
simplification colors.

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:11.210
That's our divergence theorem.

00:10:11.210 --> 00:10:14.890
So let's get rid
of it in this form,

00:10:14.890 --> 00:10:19.150
and call it minus integral
over all that stuff.

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:30.140
Then we'll have
dot, little j, to be

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:40.790
careful, r, e, omega, t, d soft.

