to how much crossing stuff out.

00:10:48.407 --> 00:10:49.990
And so like I said,
this board's going

00:10:49.990 --> 00:10:51.330
to look like a
rainbow explosion.

00:10:51.330 --> 00:10:52.872
But then we'll
rewrite it at the end.

00:10:52.872 --> 00:10:54.820
And it's going to look
a whole lot simpler.

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:59.437
So now, let's start making
some simplifications.

00:10:59.437 --> 00:11:01.270
Let's say you're an
actual reactor designer,

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:04.000
and all you care about is
how many neutrons are here.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:05.650
Of the variables
here, which one do you

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:07.060
think we care the least about?

00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:12.732
Angle, I mean do we really
care which direction

00:11:12.732 --> 00:11:13.690
the neutrons are going?

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:15.820
No, we pretty much
care, where are they?

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:18.400
And are they causing
fission or getting absorbed?

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:20.970
So let's start our
simplification board.

00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:26.200
And in blue, we'll
neglect angle.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:28.120
This is where it
starts to get fun.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:32.440
So in this case, we'll just
perform the omega integral

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:33.880
over all angles.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:36.610
We just neglect angle here.

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:41.170
We forget the omega
integral, forget omega there.

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:44.830
Away goes the 4pi, because we've
integrated overall 4pi star

00:11:44.830 --> 00:11:47.200
radians, or all solid angle.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:48.400
Let's just keep going.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:51.100
Forget the 4pi,
forget the omega,

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:57.490
forget the omega, forget the 4pi
and the omega, and the omega.

00:11:57.490 --> 00:12:01.690
Same thing here-- forget the
omega in the scattering kernel,

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:04.420
forget it in the
flux, forget it there,

00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:09.300
forget it there,
and there as well.

00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:12.775
OK, we've now completely
eliminated one variable.

00:12:12.775 --> 00:12:14.650
And all we had to do is
ditch the 4pi and one

00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:17.670
of the integrals.

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:18.300
What next?

00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:23.370
We're tracking right now
every possible position,

00:12:23.370 --> 00:12:26.280
every possible energy,
at every possible time.

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:29.280
If you want to know,
what is your flux

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:33.400
going to be in the reactor
at steady state, what

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:35.440
variable do you attack next?

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:36.520
Time.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:38.950
So let's just say this
reactor is at steady state.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:45.140
That's going to
invoke a few things.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:50.250
For one, it's going to ditch
the entire steady state term.

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:54.240
We're going to get rid of
all the ts in all the fluxes.

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:58.220
This shouldn't take
too long to do.

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:00.960
I think that's all of them.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:03.930
And the third thing is if this
reactor is at steady state,

00:13:03.930 --> 00:13:07.420
chances are we've taken
our kickstarter source out,

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:09.230
because we just needed
it to get it going.

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:11.710
But the reactor should
be self-sustaining

00:13:11.710 --> 00:13:13.310
once it's at steady state.

00:13:13.310 --> 00:13:17.530
So let's just get rid
of our source term.

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:19.700
I just want to make sure
I didn't miss any here.

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:26.080
OK, next up, let's
go with green.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:28.590
What else do you think we can
simplify about this problem?

00:13:34.710 --> 00:13:37.370
Well, if you look far enough
away from the reactor,

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:40.700
we can make an assumption
that the reactor

00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:42.500
is roughly homogeneous.

00:13:45.560 --> 00:13:47.960
In some cases, it's not
so good of an assumption,

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:51.950
like very close to anything
that has a huge absorption

00:13:51.950 --> 00:13:53.200
cross-section.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:55.490
Now, I want to explain
the physics behind this.

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:57.890
If the neutrons travel
a very long distance

00:13:57.890 --> 00:14:01.640
through any group of
materials, then those materials

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:05.900
will appear to be roughly
homogeneous to the neutrons.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:08.900
If, however, the neutrons
